<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Fikile said her show was titled Sorry For My Crimes and was about offenders apologising to their victims.While hers was targeting offenders who committed crimes against women, Yobe focuses on both male and female offenders.Fikile told Daily Sun that she had submitted her proposal to Mzansi Magic but never received any correspondence except for an automated message acknowledging receipt of her submission. “I was shocked to see the show on TV and wondered how they could do such a thing,” she said.Mabece said although the show concept was submitted in 2014, it was only included on the schedule last year in preparation for broadcast in April. “The channel believes in the development of authentic stories and handles creative ideas with integrity. “As an organisation, we receive numerous television programming proposals that may be similar or even identical, and in some instances are similar to concepts that are already under development or that have previously been developed and/or produced,” said Mabece. Fikile, however, disagreed with Mabece.“What I’ve realised is that most of these shows are produced by the same production companies,” she told the People’s Paper.“Small or unknown production companies are not given a chance.”